  <h2 class="text-xl sm:text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)] mb-5 sm:mb-6">The Science of Dog Aging: Why Breed Size Matters</h2>

  <div class="space-y-6 text-[0.8125rem] sm:text-sm text-[var(--text-secondary)] leading-relaxed">
    <p>
      For decades, dog owners relied on a simple rule: one dog year equals seven human years. While easy to remember, this formula is scientifically inaccurate and can lead to misunderstandings about your dog's true age and health needs. Modern veterinary science has revealed that dog aging is far more complex — and fascinating. Understanding how dogs age is essential for providing the best possible care at every life stage.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">The DNA Methylation Breakthrough</h3>
    <p>
      In 2019, researchers at the University of California, San Diego published a groundbreaking study in the journal <em>Cell Systems</em>. They discovered that DNA methylation — a biological clock that tracks aging at the molecular level — follows a predictable pattern in dogs that closely mirrors human aging. This led to the formula: <strong>Human Age = 16 × ln(Dog Age) + 31</strong>, where "ln" is the natural logarithm. This formula is now considered the gold standard for converting dog years to human years.
    </p>
    <p>
      This formula reveals that dogs age much faster than humans in their early years. A 1-year-old dog is equivalent to a 31-year-old human, and a 2-year-old dog is about 42 in human years. After this rapid early development, the aging rate slows down considerably. This non-linear aging pattern explains why a 2-year-old dog is already fully mature while a human of equivalent age is still a toddler.
    </p>
    <p>
      The research team analyzed DNA samples from 104 Labrador Retrievers ranging from 4 weeks to 16 years old. By comparing the methylation patterns to those of humans at various ages, they were able to establish a direct biological equivalence between dog and human aging. This study has since been replicated with other breeds, confirming that the logarithmic relationship holds true across different breed types.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Why Breed Size Changes Everything</h3>
    <p>
      The 16 × ln(dog age) + 31 formula provides a baseline, but it doesn't account for one crucial factor: breed size. Veterinary research consistently shows that smaller dogs live longer and age more slowly than larger breeds. A Chihuahua at age 10 is biologically much younger than a Great Dane at the same age. This is why our calculator adjusts the formula based on breed size categories.
    </p>
    <p>
      Scientists believe this is due to the "life history theory" — larger animals tend to grow faster, reproduce earlier, and have shorter lifespans. In dogs, this pattern is exaggerated by selective breeding. Giant breeds like Great Danes grow from puppy to full size in just 18 months — a metabolic rate that accelerates cellular aging and increases cancer risk. Small breeds like Chihuahuas take longer to reach maturity and experience slower cellular aging throughout their lives.
    </p>
    <p>
      Recent studies have shown that the difference in aging rates between small and giant breeds can be as much as 30-40%. A small dog that appears to be 12 years old may have a biological age equivalent to a 65-year-old human, while a giant breed of the same chronological age may be equivalent to an 85-year-old human. This dramatic difference underscores the importance of using a breed-size adjusted calculator rather than a one-size-fits-all approach.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Breed Size Life Expectancy Guide</h3>
    <p>
      Understanding your dog's expected lifespan helps you plan for their care at every stage:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li><strong>Small breeds</strong> (under 20 lbs): 12-16 years. Examples: Chihuahua, Pomeranian, Shih Tzu. Small breeds are known for their longevity and often remain active well into their teens.</li>
      <li><strong>Medium breeds</strong> (20-50 lbs): 10-14 years. Examples: Beagle, Bulldog, Border Collie. Medium breeds strike a balance between size and lifespan.</li>
      <li><strong>Large breeds</strong> (50-90 lbs): 8-12 years. Examples: Labrador, Golden Retriever, Husky. Large breeds are prone to joint issues and age more quickly.</li>
      <li><strong>Giant breeds</strong> (90+ lbs): 7-10 years. Examples: Great Dane, Saint Bernard, Mastiff. Giant breeds have the shortest lifespans and fastest aging rates.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Life Stages of Dogs by Breed Size</h3>
    <p>
      Dogs progress through six distinct life stages: Puppy, Teenager, Young Adult, Adult, Senior, and Elder. The timing of these transitions varies significantly by breed size. Understanding which stage your dog is in helps you provide appropriate care, nutrition, and veterinary attention.
    </p>
    <p>
      Small breed dogs remain puppies for about 6 months, reach adulthood around 2 years, and don't enter their senior years until age 11-12. In contrast, giant breed dogs enter adulthood as early as 5 years and are considered seniors by age 7-8. This means a 6-year-old Chihuahua is in its prime, while a 6-year-old Great Dane is nearing retirement. These differences have significant implications for when to switch to senior diets, how often to schedule vet visits, and what exercise routines are appropriate.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Teenager stage is particularly important for training and socialization. Small breed dogs enter this phase around 6 months and remain there until about age 2. Large and giant breeds may stay in the Teenager stage for a shorter period but often display more intense behavioral challenges due to their size and strength. Proper training during these formative months sets the foundation for a well-behaved adult dog.
    </p>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Why Accurate Age Calculation Matters</h3>
    <p>
      Knowing your dog's true biological age — not just their birthday — has practical implications for their care. Senior dogs need different nutrition, more frequent veterinary checkups, and adjusted exercise routines. They're also more susceptible to age-related conditions like arthritis, dental disease, and cognitive decline. Using an accurate age calculator helps you make informed decisions about your pet's health.
    </p>
    <p>
      By using a breed-size adjusted calculator, you can:
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li>Determine the right time to switch to senior dog food based on your dog's biological age rather than chronological age</li>
      <li>Schedule appropriate health screenings and vaccinations at the optimal times for your dog's breed size</li>
      <li>Recognize age-related behavioral changes early and adjust your care routine accordingly</li>
      <li>Plan for end-of-life care with realistic expectations based on breed-specific life expectancy data</li>
      <li>Monitor development milestones in puppies to ensure healthy growth and development</li>
    </ul>

    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">How the Dog Age Calculator Works</h3>
