    <h3 class="text-base sm:text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight text-[var(--text-primary)]">Tips for Extending Your Dog's Lifespan</h3>
    <p>
      While genetics play a significant role, lifestyle factors can help your dog live a longer, healthier life. Research shows that dogs receiving optimal care can live 2-3 years longer than dogs with substandard care, regardless of breed size.
    </p>
    <ul class="space-y-3 pl-4 sm:pl-5">
      <li><strong>Nutrition:</strong> Feed high-quality, age-appropriate food appropriate for your dog's breed size. Avoid overfeeding — obesity is a major health risk that can shorten lifespan by up to 2.5 years.</li>
      <li><strong>Exercise:</strong> Provide daily physical activity appropriate for their breed and age. Mental stimulation through puzzle toys and training is equally important for cognitive health.</li>
      <li><strong>Veterinary Care:</strong> Schedule annual checkups, maintain vaccinations, and practice parasite prevention. Senior dogs may benefit from bi-annual visits including bloodwork.</li>
      <li><strong>Dental Health:</strong> Regular teeth cleaning prevents periodontal disease, which can affect heart and kidney health. Dental disease is one of the most common preventable health issues in dogs.</li>
      <li><strong>Weight Management:</strong> Keep your dog at a healthy weight. Even moderate obesity can reduce lifespan by 2-3 years and increase the risk of diabetes, joint problems, and heart disease.</li>
      <li><strong>Mental Stimulation:</strong> Provide interactive toys, training sessions, and social interaction to keep your dog's mind sharp. Cognitive decline is slower in mentally active dogs.</li>
    </ul>

    <p class="text-[var(--text-muted)] pt-4 border-t border-[var(--border-default)]">
      <strong class="text-[var(--text-primary)]">The bottom line:</strong> Dog aging is a complex process that varies significantly by breed size. Use our breed-size adjusted calculator for accurate results and make informed decisions about your dog's health at every life stage.
    </p>
